AB  - This paper tries to explain changes in the foreign trade patterns of Israel's manufacturing sector in terms of changes in relative factor use during the period 1965–1982. Although the sector's comparative advantage lay in labor intensive goods in most of this period, changes in net exports were correlated positively with changes in human and physical capital use and negatively with changes in labor use. This was due to the expansion of capital intensive exports.
