AB  - This paper investigates the production characteristics of multinational firms operating with different orientations. Multinational firms that are export-oriented are found to be labor intensive and unskilled-labor intensive. By estimating elasticities of substitution between capital and disaggregated labor, the authors find that tax incentives that reduce capital cost for multinational firms have different effects on labor, depending on the firms' orientation.
